3nd.title: Logarithm

40j.title: What is a logarithm?
40j.text:
Logarithms are a family of [3jy functions] that map numbers to numbers. There is a logarithm function for every positive number $b$ [log_base_1 except 1], and the logarithm function for $b$, called "the logarithm base $b$" or just "log base $b$", takes an input $x$ and counts how many times you have to multiply $1$ by $b$ to get $x$. For example, the log base 10 of 1000 is 3, because you have to multiply 1 by 10 three times to get 1000. The log base $b$ of $x$ is written $\log_b(x).$

The logarithm function grows slowly, but never stops growing: for every number $n,$ no matter how large, there is a point $x_n$ such that for all $x > x_n,$ $\log_b(x) > n.$ Here's a partial graph of the logarithm base 10:


Logarithms are [3jy functions] that take a number as input and produce a number as output. There are lots of different logarithm functions: One for each positive number $b$ [log_base_1 except 1]. The logarithm function corresponding to a number $b$, called the "logarithm base $b$" or just "log base $b$", is the function that takes a number $x$ as input and counts how many times you have to multiply 1 by $b$ to get $x$. The log base $b$ of $x$ is written $\log_b(x)$. For example:

1. $\log_{10}(100) = 2,$ because you have to multiply 1 by 10 twice to get 100: $1 \cdot 10 \cdot 10 = 100.$
2. $\log_{10}(1000) = 3,$ because you have to multiply 1 by 10 three times to get 1000.
3. $\log_2(16) = 4,$ because $1 \cdot 2 \cdot 2 \cdot 2 \cdot 2 = 16.$
4. $\log_3(9) = 2,$ because $1 \cdot 3 \cdot 3 = 9.$
5. $\log_{b}(1) = 0$ for any $b$, because no matter what $b$ is, you don't need to multiply 1 by $b$ any times to get 1.
6. $\log_{b}(b) = 1$ for any $b$, because no matter what $b$ is, if you multiply 1 by $b$ once, you get $b.$
7. $\log_{1.5}(3.375) = 3,$ because $1 \cdot 1.5 \cdot 1.5 \cdot 1.5 = 3.375.$

Question: What's $\log_3(27)$?

%%hidden(Answer):
Answer: 3.
%%

Question: What's $\log_4(16)$?

%%hidden(Answer):
Answer: 2.
%%

Question: What's $\log_{10}(\text{1,000,000})$?

%%hidden(Answer):
Answer: 6.
%%

All of the examples above are cases where the answer is a whole number, because $x$ is a [power] of $b.$ Logarithms also give answers in cases where the answer is not a whole number. For example, $\log_{10}(500) \approx 2.7$. What's _that_ supposed to mean? That if you multiply 1 by 10 about 2.7 times, you get 500?

Yes, precisely! What does it mean to multiply a number by ten about 0.7 times? Well, is there a number $x$ such that if we multiply 1 by $x$ ten times, it's the same as multiplying 1 by 10 seven times? Yes: this is true for $x \approx 5.$

$$\underbrace{5 \cdot 5 \cdot \ldots 5}_\text{10 times} \approx \underbrace{10 \cdot 10 \cdot \ldots 10}_\text{7 times}$$

Multiplying by 5 (ten times) is about the same as multiplying by 10 (seven times), so multiplying by five (once) is about the same as multiplying by 10 (seven tenths of a time). Thus, $\log_{10}(500)$ is approximately 2.7: That's how many times you need to multiply 1 by 10 to get 500.

If that answer isn't satisfactory yet, don't worry: Throughout the tutorial, we'll explore both (a) what this means, and (b) why this is the "right way" to multiply a number by ten fractionally-many times.

You might also be saying to yourself, "Ok, I can see how 500 is kinda almost one times ten 2.7 times, but how do you _figure that out?_ You apparently pulled that 'ten fives is about seven tens' thing out of thin air. Where did that come from? How is the logarithm actually calculated?"

The pithy answer to that question is, you can calculate $\log_{10}(500)$ by typing "log10(500)" into [http://www.wolframalpha.com/input/?i=log10(500) Wolfram Alpha]. In seriousness, though, once you understand what it means to multiply a number by 10 a fraction of a time, there are some tricks for eyeballing logarithms and getting pretty close to the right answer. Those tricks aren't covered in this tutorial, but you can learn more over at [+eyeballing_logarithms].

In practice, outputs of logarithms are "hard to get, easy to use": The numbers that come out of a logarithm function are often [transcendental_number transcendental], in that you can't write the whole thing out (same as [pi $\pi$], [tau $\tau$], and [e $e$]). That said, logarithm functions can be approximated fairly well, and the outputs have some properties that make them very nice to work with. Historically, scientists and engineers would pay for giant tables of pre-computed logarithm values, because those sped up their practical calculations considerably. Why are the outputs of logarithm functions so convenient to use? That question will be covered later in this tutorial.

You might also be saying to yourself "Ok, I see how 500 is kinda sorta 'one times ten 2.7 times,' but what does that actually mean?"

It's hard to give a short answer to that question, but only because there are so many good answers. Logarithms mean lots of different things in lots of different contexts: They have applications to physics, computer science, number theory, psychology, information theory, engineering, and many other domains. This tutorial will touch upon a few different answers, starting with this one: Logarithms are measuring how "long" a number is, in terms of how many digits it takes to write that number down.

It may seem that numbers always take a whole number of digits to write down: 139 and 931 are both written using three digits ('9', '3', and '1'). However, as we will see, there's a sense in which 139 is barely using its third digit, while 931 is using all three of its digits to almost their full extent. Logarithms quantify this intuition, and the precise answer that they give reveals some interesting information about how many digits it costs to write a given number down.
